-- Power Grid, Reliance Communications, Tecpro Systems: India Equity Preview
-- B y   R u t h   D a v i d   a n d   R a j h k u m a r   K   S h a a w
-- 2010-10-12T02:48:03Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-12/power-grid-reliance-communications-tecpro-systems-india-equity-preview.html
The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  The Bombay Stock Exchange Sensitive Index, or  Sensex , rose
89.63, or 0.4 percent, to 20,339.89. The S&P CNX  Nifty  Index on
the National Stock Exchange advanced 0.5 percent to 6,135.85.
The  BSE 200 Index  increased 0.6 percent to 2,593.17.  SGX S&P CNX
Nifty Index futures  for October delivery declined 0.1 percent to
6,148 as of 10:38 a.m. in Singapore.  Bharti Airtel Ltd.  (BHARTI IN): The largest mobile-phone
operator and  Idea Cellular Ltd.  (IDEA IN) were raised to “buy”
from “hold” at BNP Paribas, which said it was turning
“positive” on the industry amid signs competitive and
regulatory concerns may be easing.  The brokerage raised Bharti’s share-price estimate to 440
rupees from 300 rupees and increased Idea Cellular’s stock
forecast to 85 rupees from 65 rupees, according to a report by
 Sameer Naringrekar  and  Kunal Vora . Bharti decreased 2.9 percent
to 342.85 rupees. Idea was unchanged at 70.75 rupees.  JSW Energy Ltd.  (JSW IN): JSW group has emerged as the
frontrunner to buy a controlling stake in Canada’s CIC Energy
Corp., the Economic Times reported, without saying where it got
the information from. The acquisition may cost between $450 and
$500 million, the paper said. JSW Energy climbed 0.4 percent to
123 rupees.  MRF Ltd  (MRF IN): The tire maker’s plants in Punducherry
and Arakkonam, in the nation’s south, have been halted by
workers’ strikes, the Business Standard reported, without saying
from where it got the information. The stock dropped 0.1 percent
to 8,779.9 rupees.  Power Grid Corp. of India Ltd.  (PWGR IN): The state-run
company has approached banks to help it raise 15 billion rupees
($338 million), two people familiar with the matter said
yesterday. The shares advanced 0.4 percent to 109.9 rupees.  Reliance Communications Ltd.  (RCOM IN): India’s second-
largest mobile phone operator may sell bonds or borrow from
banks overseas to repay about 86 billion rupees of debt,
according to a person with direct knowledge of the plan.  Separately, the shares of billionaire  Anil Ambani -
controlled company were raised to “equal-weight” from
“underweight” at Morgan Stanley, which said the stock now
looks “fairly valued” after having underperformed in the last
three months. The brokerage has a share-price estimate of 180
rupees, according to a report by  Vinay Jaising  and  Surabhi Chandna . The shares climbed 2 percent to 184.2 rupees.  Tecpro Systems Ltd. (TPRO IN): The engineering company will
debut on exchanges today. Its initial share sale last month
raised 2.68 billion rupees, according to data compiled by
